ears":"1918-1919","enlisted_date":"1918-08-26","discharged_date":"1919-01-17","notes":"Enlisted August 26, 1918; discharged January 17, 1919. Five-month service window — enlisted in the final months of the war and was discharged shortly after the Armistice."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Enlisted as Armistice loomed, served five months","body":"Douglas Montgomery Pierpont enlisted in the U.S. Army on August 26, 1918 — eleven weeks before the November 11 Armistice ended World War I. He was discharged on January 17, 1919, having served roughly five months total, including the war's final phase and the immediate aftermath. He died fifty-five years later at the Veterans Administration Hospital in West Haven Connecticut, age seventy-nine."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Vice president of cousin-named gear company","body":"Pierpont was Vice President of the Snow-Nabstedt Gear Corporation in Connecticut — a corporate name built from two cousin-family surnames he knew intimately. 'Snow' was Levi Tracy Snow, husband of his distant cousin Sila Harrison Pierpont (daughter of his grand-uncle Cornelius). 'Nabstedt' was Arthur Theodore Nabstedt, who married Sila's daughter Ruth Canfield Snow. He held the role through the WWII industrial-machinery boom."}],"slug":"douglas-pierpont-1894"},"X00404":{"id":"X00404","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1900},"death":{"year":1987},"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD1299","children_ids":["HD1303","HD1304","HD1305","HD1306","HD1307"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Edna Irene Thomas","first_name":"Edna","middle_name":"